1
00:00:00,942 --> 00:00:19,591
namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:19,690 --> 00:00:36,484
Namo tassa bhagavado arahato samma sambuddhasa homage to the Buddha, the blessed, no-law and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:36,505 --> 00:00:39,787
Okay, so we're going to approach the problem of karma.

4
00:00:42,930 --> 00:00:49,156
The first thing is the question of how does the Buddha describe how anything happens?

5
00:00:50,707 --> 00:00:52,209
How do things happen?

6
00:00:53,530 --> 00:00:57,137
And it's called the law of this and that.

7
00:00:58,057 --> 00:00:58,398
Okay?

8
00:00:58,539 --> 00:01:01,884
The specific law of conditionality is also called that.

9
00:01:02,725 --> 00:01:08,774
And I shall read the equations.

10
00:01:11,216 --> 00:01:11,378
Okay?

11
00:01:12,118 --> 00:01:14,703
When this is, that is.

12
00:01:16,465 --> 00:01:18,367
From the arising of this,

13
00:01:18,787 --> 00:01:33,102
comes the arising of that when this isn't that isn't from the stopping of this comes the stopping of that got it?

14
00:01:36,605 --> 00:01:38,248
so when I first read it I thought what?

15
00:01:41,090 --> 00:01:45,756
so if we now put two statements together it becomes a little more obvious

16
00:01:46,917 --> 00:02:09,735
so the first one is from the arising of this comes the arising of that and from the stopping of this comes the stopping of that so this is linear cause and effect okay so the fact that you came here right you decided at some point to come on the course

17
00:02:10,254 --> 00:02:13,758
you made that decision, you empowered it, and you came here.

18
00:02:14,080 --> 00:02:18,745
So from the arising of that, you arose at Gaia House.

19
00:02:19,286 --> 00:02:19,586
Okay?

20
00:02:20,747 --> 00:02:31,099
If you had thought about it, or you had some reason that you couldn't come, because you stopped coming, you did not arise at Gaia House.

21
00:02:31,520 --> 00:02:37,387
This is a sort of linear way that we would normally, generally think about cause and effect.

22
00:02:37,787 --> 00:02:38,288
Okay?

23
00:02:40,342 --> 00:03:09,641
the other one is when this is, that is and when this isn't, that isn't now that brings us directly into the present moment where things happen simultaneously so we all arrive here and the course begins and every time you arrive it's a new occasion for meditating together, listening to talk

24
00:03:10,330 --> 00:03:14,234
If you didn't arrive, it wouldn't happen, right?

25
00:03:14,334 --> 00:03:16,156
It's extremely simple, okay?

26
00:03:17,097 --> 00:03:23,805
Now, if it were just linear, then where would creativity come in?

27
00:03:25,165 --> 00:03:31,432
Wouldn't it suggest a repetitiveness, a monotony, one after the other?

28
00:03:31,453 --> 00:03:37,840
There'd be nothing to stop the original intention, it would just keep repeating itself, yeah?

29
00:03:39,236 --> 00:03:55,299
if it were just immediate then there would be no order so it would be chaotic things would arise, collapse and then for no other reason things would arise and collapse no?

30
00:03:55,318 --> 00:04:08,737
when you put these two together you get a cause coming from the past into the present moment where it meets other causes coming from the past into this present moment

31
00:04:09,747 --> 00:04:18,963
So it's much more clearer to talk about how things happen as a process of contingency.

32
00:04:19,944 --> 00:04:33,548
Every moment, lines of decisions, not only that, nature, whatever's happening in the outside world, the birds, constantly coming to meet into this present moment.

33
00:04:35,050 --> 00:04:35,451
Okay?

34
00:04:37,067 --> 00:04:53,110
And so when we think about karma in that sense, you can see it's very difficult to sort out what's my personal karma, what's the karma from somebody else, what's the karma of the situation, but we'll come to that in a minute.

35
00:04:53,130 --> 00:05:02,704
So if we have that idea of contingency rather than some linear process, we're getting close to what the Buddha talked about.

36
00:05:03,899 --> 00:05:19,819
And this is suggestive of the chaos theory, some of you might know, where an initial impulse supported by conditions just changes and grows or diminishes.

37
00:05:20,360 --> 00:05:25,526
So the example that's normally given is the weather.

38
00:05:25,545 --> 00:05:32,774
So one scientist said, if there's a butterfly wing in the south of America,

39
00:05:33,430 --> 00:05:40,036
with supporting conditions becomes a tornado in North America.

40
00:05:40,055 --> 00:05:47,963
So in any given moment, we don't actually know what is coming into that present moment.

41
00:05:47,983 --> 00:05:56,190
Luckily, when you live in a peaceful country, et cetera, et cetera, you can almost, shall we say, predict what's going to happen.

42
00:05:56,211 --> 00:06:01,175
But of course, that would lead us into a delusion that the future is predictable.

43
00:06:10,285 --> 00:06:19,240
So that specific conditionality is underlying everything.

44
00:06:19,259 --> 00:06:24,829
It not only underlies what's happening in the world out there, it underlies our own minds.

45
00:06:26,072 --> 00:06:32,562
Because you don't know what is coming in from the outside and how you're responding from the inside.

46
00:06:33,809 --> 00:06:37,415
So it's a constant moment after moment creativity.

47
00:06:37,956 --> 00:06:43,687
Nothing can repeat itself.

48
00:06:47,194 --> 00:06:53,927
Now, when we come to the actual karma that's important,

49
00:06:54,228 --> 00:07:04,377
which is our model actions, our ethical actions, again, it's very difficult to know what is actually...

50
00:07:05,059 --> 00:07:12,045
When we're receiving something, when something is happening, to know whether it's personal karma or not.

51
00:07:16,009 --> 00:07:18,733
The Buddha talks about five different laws.

52
00:07:18,899 --> 00:07:45,108
and the first one is called the law of heat and it refers to just basic chemistry and physics so in other words something like a tsunami okay so a tsunami is caused by shifting plates etc etc and when the tsunami hit Sri Lanka Thailand a place like that of course a lot of people died now

53
00:07:46,927 --> 00:07:52,956
Some would have thought that this was caused by bad karma in the past.

54
00:07:53,577 --> 00:07:57,824
Somewhere in the past they'd ground a few dogs or something.

55
00:07:57,884 --> 00:08:03,673
They'd have to find some sort of excuse for that tsunami creating such suffering.

56
00:08:04,514 --> 00:08:10,523
Others would have been a bit more philosophical, shall we say, in the sense of, well, everything's impermanent.

57
00:08:11,920 --> 00:08:23,134
So, it was these sorts of arguments that undermine the sort of strength of trauma that people can have when something like that happens.

58
00:08:24,495 --> 00:08:37,009
And I was told that when Western counsellors went out there to see if they could help, they found that people weren't particularly traumatized because they have this understanding.

59
00:08:37,791 --> 00:08:39,693
Nothing is safe, nothing is permanent.

60
00:08:40,254 --> 00:08:41,556
Things happen.

61
00:08:43,256 --> 00:08:52,769
So that's one law, which is to do with just nature, you might say.

62
00:08:52,788 --> 00:08:57,434
The next one is to do with seed, that's what it's called, so it's genetics.

63
00:08:58,395 --> 00:09:07,527
So now the body you've ended up with is not your personal karma, we know it, it's part of the family, it's coming from your family's genetic history.

64
00:09:07,995 --> 00:09:16,442
So, if for instance somebody is born with a genetic disease, that is not personal karma.

65
00:09:16,461 --> 00:09:20,232
That is something that has happened through that birth process.

66
00:09:20,551 --> 00:09:29,582
If somebody has a bad birth process and ends up with trauma, that isn't their personal karma.

67
00:09:29,602 --> 00:09:32,086
It's not as though they were meant to have that.

68
00:09:32,105 --> 00:09:40,837
It's just that when you enter into this life form, things happen, and that's the end of it.

69
00:09:42,184 --> 00:09:58,085
So you have to be careful of that because sometimes I think people get confused that what happens to them physically through their genetics is somehow caused because of some bad action, always in the past life.

70
00:09:58,745 --> 00:10:03,572
The third one is the citta, the mind.

71
00:10:04,594 --> 00:10:06,034
And this is our psychology.

72
00:10:06,135 --> 00:10:09,659
So here we're talking about just the basic ability of the mind.

73
00:10:09,860 --> 00:10:15,365
its ability to think, to speak, to solve problems, etc., etc.

74
00:10:15,485 --> 00:10:19,789
So it's just what we would normally think of as our psychology.

75
00:10:21,111 --> 00:10:37,908
And again, you know, we're born with this body, perhaps the brain is not quite so quick as somebody else's brain, but if you were to say that this is my personal karma, in other words, I've caused it because of some action in the past,

76
00:10:38,361 --> 00:10:44,173
that would be either untrue or unprovable.

77
00:10:45,216 --> 00:10:58,462
It seems the whole body-mind process that we have is not specifically caused by moral or immoral actions in the past.

78
00:10:59,471 --> 00:11:03,957
The fourth one is karma, but I'll just go on to the next one, which is dharma.

79
00:11:03,977 --> 00:11:05,779
And that's all the teachings of the Buddha.

80
00:11:06,360 --> 00:11:11,086
So the Four Noble Truths, Eightfold Path, Dependence, Origination, that you heard.

81
00:11:11,126 --> 00:11:18,916
All these are a dharma, the teachings which allow us to escape from suffering.

82
00:11:18,936 --> 00:11:20,398
Okay, so that's the fifth category.

83
00:11:21,158 --> 00:11:23,522
So if we go back to karma,

84
00:11:25,644 --> 00:11:35,193
The normal, the progress, so an intention comes, we've seen that clearly, we empower it, and it produces an action.

85
00:11:36,174 --> 00:11:39,417
When you repeat similar actions, then you get a habit.

86
00:11:40,138 --> 00:11:43,400
And when you put all your habits together, that's your personality.

87
00:11:44,022 --> 00:11:48,826
Once you've got a personality and character, then you're moving towards your destiny.

88
00:11:49,866 --> 00:11:53,289
So things will happen because of your character and personality.

89
00:11:53,741 --> 00:12:05,692
So, our job from a karmic point of view is to realize that it's our moral decisions that are going to have the effect as to whether we suffer or not.

90
00:12:06,533 --> 00:12:06,854
Okay?

91
00:12:07,794 --> 00:12:14,922
Now, in the Buddha's own experience, when he went through the process of awakening, he saw three things clearly.

92
00:12:15,341 --> 00:12:21,268
He saw all his past lives, which showed him how he ended up being fully liberated.

93
00:12:21,534 --> 00:12:33,668
He saw how beings moved from one realm to another according to their moral, ethical actions, and he knew that he himself had no more defilements.

94
00:12:33,727 --> 00:12:35,610
He was purified of his defilements.

95
00:12:37,272 --> 00:12:51,407
So what was a personal law for him, seeing the process of his life after life and how he became fully liberated, then became a universal law as far as he was concerned.

96
00:12:51,572 --> 00:13:10,729
So our actions, our intended actions, even habitual actions, actions that we don't consciously decide but have a moral or ethical quality to them, are going to produce certain results.

97
00:13:11,535 --> 00:13:17,849
Now, the general law is, if you do something good, well, good comes of it.

98
00:13:18,169 --> 00:13:21,115
And if you do something harmful, some harm comes of it.

99
00:13:22,720 --> 00:13:23,301
But,

100
00:13:24,192 --> 00:13:32,484
It's a case of recognizing that even if you do something good, you could undermine it by doing something harmful.

101
00:13:32,504 --> 00:13:38,993
And if you do something harmful, you can undermine its effect by doing something good.

102
00:13:39,994 --> 00:13:53,472
So, for instance, if I were to say a sharp word to somebody and I upset them, I very easily stop the possibility of their hating me and doing things horrible to me by simply apologizing.

103
00:13:53,722 --> 00:14:03,575
So it's not as though there's some sort of rigid process that once we do something harmful that will happen, right?

104
00:14:03,595 --> 00:14:12,686
Because it goes into a sort of matrix out there in the world and a matrix in us.

105
00:14:13,427 --> 00:14:17,351
And the effect we can never be absolutely sure of.

106
00:14:17,533 --> 00:14:26,633
So, for instance, there was a charity which sent clothes, second-hand clothes, to an African country.

107
00:14:27,674 --> 00:14:31,003
And what happened was it undermined the local tailor trade.

108
00:14:31,683 --> 00:14:34,931
And in doing so, it undermined the local economy.

109
00:14:35,272 --> 00:14:36,453
So they had to pull out.

110
00:14:37,024 --> 00:14:45,695
So compassionate action also has to be accompanied by wisdom, by knowledge.

111
00:14:45,815 --> 00:14:48,778
You can't just do something because you think it's a good thing.

112
00:14:49,818 --> 00:15:02,913
So there they did something which they thought was good, and it was, there's no problem with it, but within the situation it created an unfortunate situation and they had to withdraw.

113
00:15:03,332 --> 00:15:18,202
So, you can see that the whole process of karma is very difficult to work with if you're going to be logical, if you're going to try and think about consequences.

114
00:15:18,587 --> 00:15:27,340
Because you can do something, a person might do something terrible, but because of the surrounding situation, nothing happens on it.

115
00:15:27,841 --> 00:15:34,850
So we know that so many burglaries are not being even approached by the police.

116
00:15:35,270 --> 00:15:38,335
So there's a lot of burglars out there who are getting away with it.

117
00:15:38,315 --> 00:15:43,900
Now, they might be getting away with it in terms of society, but not within the heart.

118
00:15:43,921 --> 00:15:57,336
Because every time they Virgo, they are actually developing that desire of taking something not really given and enjoying it, and taking it for their own personal enjoyment.

119
00:15:58,037 --> 00:16:03,342
And at some point, yeah, there has to be some reflection of that.

120
00:16:03,644 --> 00:16:14,261
either in themselves as something which is harmful and there's a sense of guilt and shame or they get caught and they get stuck in prison.

121
00:16:16,164 --> 00:16:27,566
In the process of rebirth, again, it's not as though it's a linear thing, that in the next lifetime they will be caught and hanged.

122
00:16:28,126 --> 00:16:28,807
It's not quite...

123
00:16:29,548 --> 00:16:34,577
It simply is that when they are reborn, they take with them that attitude.

124
00:16:35,239 --> 00:16:36,721
And at some point,

125
00:16:36,701 --> 00:16:48,004
You know, the universe, you might say, the cosmos, or the people around them, perhaps a bit more grounded, begin to mirror back to them exactly what they're doing.

126
00:16:48,725 --> 00:16:55,099
So there's a sort of moral justice that's written into this process, as far as the Buddha's concerned.

127
00:16:55,653 --> 00:17:01,000
Now, some of the talks mention this rebirth business.

128
00:17:01,039 --> 00:17:05,046
Do remember that this isn't a belief system.

129
00:17:05,425 --> 00:17:15,720
It's not as though you have to believe any of this stuff, because the process of liberation is the process of investigation.

130
00:17:15,970 --> 00:17:20,763
If you believe something, then there's a possibility you don't make it true for you.

131
00:17:20,805 --> 00:17:25,198
So, you know, it's just, I believe what the Buddha said, and therefore I'll become enlightened.

132
00:17:25,218 --> 00:17:26,300
It doesn't work like that.

133
00:17:26,787 --> 00:17:34,517
So he's always putting to us certain propositions and saying, is this true for you?

134
00:17:36,019 --> 00:17:40,605
So it's not a matter of whether we believe in rebirth or not.

135
00:17:40,845 --> 00:17:44,829
It's a case of just leaving open that possibility.

136
00:17:44,990 --> 00:17:46,972
Don't shut it down.

137
00:17:48,218 --> 00:17:54,406
Now, I'm reminded of Pascal's dictum.

138
00:17:54,426 --> 00:17:57,299
Pascal was an 18th century mathematician.

139
00:17:57,517 --> 00:18:06,151
And it was the growth of science and everything, and there was people who didn't believe in God anymore, positivists and things like that.

140
00:18:06,191 --> 00:18:16,248
And what he said was, there may or may not be a God, but it might be wise to act as if there was one.

141
00:18:17,589 --> 00:18:23,118
There may or may not be rebirth, but it might be wise to act as if there is rebirth.

142
00:18:25,124 --> 00:18:31,877
So that actually takes us to this law.

143
00:18:32,318 --> 00:18:41,698
So we've understood this basic underlying conditionality, which is to do with contingency.

144
00:18:41,897 --> 00:18:42,779
It's not linear.

145
00:18:43,641 --> 00:18:46,406
You never know exactly what's going to happen.

146
00:18:46,386 --> 00:19:08,194
And then within that we have all these laws to do with nature, to do with hereditary, to do with psychology, which of course is also to do with society, and I'll come back to that, which takes us into social karma.

147
00:19:08,214 --> 00:19:11,719
And then finally there's the karma, which is this specific area

148
00:19:12,086 --> 00:19:15,953
to do with suffering, and finally this dharma.

149
00:19:16,414 --> 00:19:20,280
So be clear about the ethical part.

150
00:19:20,300 --> 00:19:29,416
The ethical part, what the Buddha is saying is that it's the way we behave ethically which is either going to make us happy or unhappy.

151
00:19:30,779 --> 00:19:35,647
And that's what we've been really investigating with this whole business of, say, eating.

152
00:19:36,319 --> 00:19:48,136
So we notice that when we fall into a habit of me or mine, some level of greed or self-service, there's always going to be this dissatisfaction.

153
00:19:49,479 --> 00:19:52,403
It's just that, and that's where the suffering lies.

154
00:19:52,423 --> 00:19:58,092
The suffering lies in trying to seek happiness in the wrong place.

155
00:19:58,712 --> 00:20:06,722
And this seeking of happiness in the sensual world is the cause of all our mental diseases.

156
00:20:10,929 --> 00:20:17,136
So if we go back to, say, even a child.

157
00:20:17,837 --> 00:20:21,041
So if a child is abused, you see,

158
00:20:21,190 --> 00:20:25,558
And this is quite difficult to sort of accept.

159
00:20:26,181 --> 00:20:32,292
If a child is abused, the reaction is the child's reaction.

160
00:20:32,795 --> 00:20:38,727
It's not the reaction, it's not caused directly remember by the person who's abused the child.

161
00:20:39,432 --> 00:20:46,521
The abuse is physical, it may be emotional, but the suffering comes because of that reaction.

162
00:20:46,923 --> 00:20:50,248
There, the trauma is an inward process.

163
00:20:51,048 --> 00:20:56,596
So for instance, if somebody came and hit me on the nose and shouted at me, right?

164
00:20:56,917 --> 00:21:01,604
The pain stops here, and the feeling of anger hits me here.

165
00:21:02,465 --> 00:21:08,815
Everything else is an internal process as a reaction, and that's my trauma.

166
00:21:09,452 --> 00:21:12,699
That's why I can be cured of it.

167
00:21:12,719 --> 00:21:23,881
If my suffering was caused by you, in order to bring about the end of my suffering, I'd have to get rid of you.

168
00:21:25,243 --> 00:21:29,511
It's only because my suffering is caused by me that I can be rid of it.

169
00:21:29,551 --> 00:21:31,596
Yeah?

170
00:21:33,971 --> 00:21:38,317
That doesn't, when we think about that, doesn't excuse the abuser.

171
00:21:39,357 --> 00:21:46,968
It's not a case of saying, oh well, the abuser didn't cause the trauma, so we don't have to worry about that.

172
00:21:47,147 --> 00:21:47,387
No.

173
00:21:47,848 --> 00:21:55,557
The abuser also has to accept that he was the initial impetus that caused the whole problem.

174
00:21:56,990 --> 00:22:03,723
Yeah, well, the triggers are just opening up that trauma.

175
00:22:03,743 --> 00:22:05,968
So it's an occasion for the person to work with it.

176
00:22:08,432 --> 00:22:08,854
Why not?

177
00:22:10,237 --> 00:22:16,769
I mean, just in my own experience, I've had true childhood traumas come up.

178
00:22:16,884 --> 00:22:28,779
Now, when we talk about traumas, there's undoubtedly, you know, harm done by parents, family members, and others, of course, the children, that's the last one.

179
00:22:29,279 --> 00:22:34,846
But remember also that the child comes in with their own mentality.

180
00:22:35,728 --> 00:22:41,796
So, in my own experience, I walked into the front room,

181
00:22:42,298 --> 00:22:44,342
My grandfather was sat on a chair.

182
00:22:44,682 --> 00:22:49,410
I couldn't have been much more than two years old, two, three months, four months.

183
00:22:50,451 --> 00:22:53,715
And I went to shake him and he didn't move.

184
00:22:54,196 --> 00:22:56,820
So I said to myself, they've killed him.

185
00:22:57,181 --> 00:22:58,522
Now they're going to kill me.

186
00:22:59,545 --> 00:23:04,593
When that memory came to mind, I was that child.

187
00:23:04,633 --> 00:23:09,740
That's always a sign of a trauma that you relive that moment totally.

188
00:23:09,759 --> 00:23:11,563
And it's the same with the past life.

189
00:23:12,640 --> 00:23:17,509
If you have a memory from the past life, you remember it as that person.

190
00:23:18,109 --> 00:23:21,375
You're not this person remembering something, okay?

191
00:23:21,576 --> 00:23:23,941
That's the telltale sign of the past life.

192
00:23:25,423 --> 00:23:31,174
And my body was suffused with fear, right?

193
00:23:31,255 --> 00:23:32,135
It was total.

194
00:23:33,419 --> 00:23:34,580
Fortunately,

195
00:23:34,747 --> 00:23:42,296
My father was still alive, so I said to my dad, I said, it was me that found grandfather dead in a chair in the front room.

196
00:23:43,336 --> 00:23:45,278
He said, no, I was living, he was in bed when he died.

197
00:23:46,079 --> 00:23:46,361
You see?

198
00:23:46,421 --> 00:23:55,411
So the child, somewhere in me there was a fear, and I can only presume that my parents were arguing, and I decided they were arguing against me.

199
00:23:56,152 --> 00:23:59,556
I don't know, but that's what happened, right?

200
00:24:02,167 --> 00:24:12,383
So, it's good for us to remember that a child is also living this imaginative life arising out of their own particular conditioning.

201
00:24:22,978 --> 00:24:32,090
Now, I want to move to an area which isn't often dealt with, I think, and this is really just an attempt

202
00:24:32,662 --> 00:24:38,670
Sometimes we talk about collective or social karma.

203
00:24:38,970 --> 00:24:46,961
And the last century saw three of these three secular ideologies.

204
00:24:47,781 --> 00:24:56,593
The first was communism, the second was nationalism, national socialism, and the third was neoliberalism.

205
00:24:57,011 --> 00:25:04,845
And an ideology always has some Shangri-La that you're moving towards.

206
00:25:05,605 --> 00:25:11,575
If you do this and this and this, you end up with being tremendously rich, or tremendously happy, or etc.

207
00:25:11,596 --> 00:25:12,135
etc.

208
00:25:12,958 --> 00:25:18,125
In which case, it always loses its grounding in what's happening in the present moment.

209
00:25:18,307 --> 00:25:28,763
And as Marx said of capitalism, and he could have said it of communism as well, all these isms have the seeds of their own destruction.

210
00:25:29,644 --> 00:25:36,756
And the reason is that they're always trying to fit the present moment into some future heavenly place.

211
00:25:37,477 --> 00:25:37,616
Okay?

212
00:25:39,319 --> 00:25:40,300
So now this...

213
00:25:40,500 --> 00:25:45,648
I'm fortunate to be old enough to have lived through two different systems.

214
00:25:45,950 --> 00:25:55,481
So the system that came here after the war had a lot of effects of socialism, a sort of very watered-down communism.

215
00:25:56,304 --> 00:26:10,422
And this was expressed through the national health system, through support for people to move from one class to another, through the system of grammar schools and all that.

216
00:26:10,586 --> 00:26:15,954
And the caring was taken on by the state.

217
00:26:16,655 --> 00:26:25,689
So there was a whole movement after the war to create a state-based service which was for the benefit of the people.

218
00:26:26,550 --> 00:26:29,575
Running alongside that was industry.

219
00:26:29,807 --> 00:26:40,098
And I remember having discussions or being told that if you went into industry, you got more money, but your job was insecure.

220
00:26:40,859 --> 00:26:48,748
But if you worked in one of the government-based systems, then of course your job was secure.

221
00:26:48,909 --> 00:26:51,030
So if you became a teacher, your job was secure.

222
00:26:52,311 --> 00:26:55,015
And that was the little bargain that you had between the two.

223
00:26:55,675 --> 00:26:57,637
And they ran fairly parallel.

224
00:26:58,511 --> 00:27:05,359
But then, as always, you've got this grit which is going to undermine the system.

225
00:27:06,240 --> 00:27:12,126
And what happened was, of course, was the workers began to gain tremendous power.

226
00:27:12,988 --> 00:27:16,771
And perhaps it can be argued they went over the top.

227
00:27:17,353 --> 00:27:21,297
And I know that, for instance, the...

228
00:27:21,277 --> 00:27:34,550
The union boss, the head of the car union, the automobile union, Scanlon, confessed that he'd actually ruined the mobile industry because they were demanding more and more and more.

229
00:27:35,211 --> 00:27:38,815
And of course then we got Mrs Thatcher.

230
00:27:38,835 --> 00:27:45,382
Now what Mrs Thatcher did, of course, was to begin to change the system to neoliberalism.

231
00:27:46,442 --> 00:27:50,186
Now this neoliberalism is another ideology.

232
00:27:52,951 --> 00:28:07,412
And it's a sort of corruption of capitalism in a way, because even, I'm not an economist by the way, this is just general knowledge, you'll have to check it all out for yourselves afterwards.

233
00:28:10,436 --> 00:28:20,612
When Smith wrote the basic book on capitalism, paper on capitalism, he always had a sense of social justice in there.

234
00:28:20,592 --> 00:28:31,904
And when he talked about the hidden hand, what he was being, according to one writer, sardonic.

235
00:28:32,425 --> 00:28:45,400
Because all these selfish, self-serving businessmen unwittingly were creating jobs that were helping people who would have been poor.

236
00:28:45,901 --> 00:28:47,663
It was a side effect.

237
00:28:48,030 --> 00:28:51,563
And that's what he meant by the hidden hand.

238
00:28:51,583 --> 00:28:58,767
Now what neoliberalism did is it made the market the purpose and be-all of society.

239
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:02,185
So everybody has to be part of the market.

240
00:29:03,228 --> 00:29:06,513
And everybody is an entrepreneur.

241
00:29:06,734 --> 00:29:09,619
You've got to make your way in the market.

242
00:29:10,722 --> 00:29:15,471
Now, we've seen Uber in London trying to do that.

243
00:29:15,491 --> 00:29:20,821
And there's an immediate lowering of wages because you have to bid for a lift.

244
00:29:20,801 --> 00:29:23,325
to take the person.

245
00:29:23,345 --> 00:29:24,385
You have to bid for it.

246
00:29:24,465 --> 00:29:28,991
So three or four bid comes up, and of course it's the lowest that gets the lift.

247
00:29:29,712 --> 00:29:33,336
So there's a constant pushing down of wages.

248
00:29:33,717 --> 00:29:35,378
It just happens naturally.

249
00:29:35,398 --> 00:29:40,545
Luckily, they were taken to law, and now they have to employ people, etc., etc.

250
00:29:41,246 --> 00:29:48,615
But we saw a worse case just recently with the P&O ferries, where they simply fired 800 people.

251
00:29:48,747 --> 00:29:55,842
because they were losing 100 million a year, but they just paid out 270 million to their shareholders.

252
00:29:56,182 --> 00:30:02,015
So the idea that the money will trickle down is actually a tsunami going up, as we know.

253
00:30:02,055 --> 00:30:05,321
That's not something that we're aware of.

254
00:30:05,301 --> 00:30:14,782
So the fundamental attitude is acquisitiveness, it's to get money because when you get money you can do what you want.

255
00:30:15,523 --> 00:30:24,103
So greed is actually driving the system and what it does is it puts us into an aggressive competitiveness.

256
00:30:24,573 --> 00:30:27,700
And this has sort of come into...

257
00:30:27,720 --> 00:30:30,446
It was never defined.

258
00:30:30,547 --> 00:30:34,435
It was just slipped in as a sort of economic program.

259
00:30:35,258 --> 00:30:40,068
And it was never quite defined as to what was the underlying understanding.

260
00:30:41,432 --> 00:30:41,551
Right?

261
00:30:41,886 --> 00:30:55,949
And it's coming to, I think Carl mentioned it, that on these programs, from America especially, when everybody says, I'll do something, they're always asking how much they get, how much do you want?

262
00:30:56,490 --> 00:31:00,635
Everything has to be some sort of transaction, okay?

263
00:31:01,877 --> 00:31:07,826
The idea of giving something or doing something for nothing sort of goes out of the window, okay?

264
00:31:08,599 --> 00:31:37,881
Now this has become a sort of general feeling in our societies so that when the Covid hit everybody suddenly realised they were neighbours and they were helping each other and they said, oh look, we're neighbours, we can help each other and it was just like a revelation because before you just worked out your own life and they lived over there

265
00:31:39,176 --> 00:31:51,500
Okay, so now what happens is that it's the one with the best talent, with the greatest greed, with the ability to fight this competition that's going to win.

266
00:31:52,221 --> 00:31:54,846
And now that's not what Darwin said, right?

267
00:31:54,865 --> 00:31:55,988
It's not greed that's...

268
00:31:56,429 --> 00:32:02,400
He says that it wasn't the strongest or the most intelligent, but the most adaptable, right?

269
00:32:02,751 --> 00:32:10,844
But it's been translated through neoliberalism as greed is good and competition is what we really want, an aggressive competition.

270
00:32:12,625 --> 00:32:19,015
Okay, so in a pure neoliberalist situation, the worker has no rights.

271
00:32:19,777 --> 00:32:23,561
They have to negotiate with the employer.

272
00:32:24,942 --> 00:32:31,394
The government must keep away from restricting the market.

273
00:32:31,414 --> 00:32:41,856
So if you remember, those of you who know Gordon Brown, the light touch, well, it led to this huge collapse in 2008 because the banks were greedy.

274
00:32:41,876 --> 00:32:43,760
Everybody's greedy, yeah?

275
00:32:44,163 --> 00:32:52,574
Trade unions are simply not to be allowed because they just undermine this bargaining, this entrepreneurial spirit.

276
00:32:54,036 --> 00:33:01,526
And so just recently, Amazon went and fired all the managers in New York because the workers were beginning to form a union.

277
00:33:02,926 --> 00:33:11,097
And charities, charities are a real bind because they're doing something which you could make money out of.

278
00:33:12,057 --> 00:33:19,366
So these things are not particularly welcomed and it undermines the entrepreneurial spirit.

279
00:33:20,443 --> 00:33:23,648
What about the unemployed?

280
00:33:24,349 --> 00:33:27,314
What about the sick and the aged and the mentally ill?

281
00:33:28,675 --> 00:33:30,919
Well, they become drags on the whole system.

282
00:33:30,979 --> 00:33:32,942
They're just drawing money out of the system.

283
00:33:33,762 --> 00:33:37,248
And you shouldn't tax people who've made all this money.

284
00:33:37,407 --> 00:33:38,650
That's simply not fair.

285
00:33:39,090 --> 00:33:42,154
Because they've actually won in the system.

286
00:33:42,675 --> 00:33:48,865
So the only way to make it work within a neoliberal system is to privatize it.

287
00:33:48,845 --> 00:33:50,567
And then somebody makes the money.

288
00:33:51,047 --> 00:33:54,270
Somebody rents the system out to you.

289
00:33:54,290 --> 00:33:57,394
And this is exactly what's happening now with our GPs.

290
00:33:57,413 --> 00:34:02,500
They're selling it to a company called Centene, which even the Daily Mail calls rapacious.

291
00:34:03,200 --> 00:34:04,842
And it's just going on all the time.

292
00:34:06,063 --> 00:34:07,244
I hated to give you all this.

293
00:34:10,849 --> 00:34:13,130
It was just bad news.

294
00:34:13,329 --> 00:34:16,775
Now, when you get to...

295
00:34:16,855 --> 00:34:21,121
So, in the system, there's no particular social responsibility.

296
00:34:22,903 --> 00:34:24,826
By the way, everything, of course, is privatized.

297
00:34:25,527 --> 00:34:34,360
The water, the electricity, the transport, everything becomes owned by somebody else who take their little percentage.

298
00:34:34,728 --> 00:34:44,202
All these, the electricity, for instance, I know because we had to have three-phase electricity put into our centre.

299
00:34:44,884 --> 00:34:48,429
And I was talking to the man who organised it and they take 10%.

300
00:34:49,230 --> 00:34:54,898
Now, I don't know whether that's 10% after they've paid their shareholders or before, but they take 10%.

301
00:34:55,420 --> 00:34:56,762
So they're all 10%ers.

302
00:34:57,041 --> 00:35:02,170
All these people at home, these companies, have all taken their little 10%.

303
00:35:04,123 --> 00:35:04,684
Okay.

304
00:35:06,206 --> 00:35:17,798
And this really comes down to this wonderful phrase which most of you will remember from Maggie Thatcher, that there is no such thing as society, there's only individuals, right?

305
00:35:17,818 --> 00:35:20,440
Now in doing that, you see, you isolate people.

306
00:35:21,181 --> 00:35:22,704
One person is up against the other.

307
00:35:23,143 --> 00:35:28,590
And what's missing there, of course, is that the whole is always greater than the sum of the parts.

308
00:35:29,351 --> 00:35:33,135
When you have people together, you create community.

309
00:35:33,385 --> 00:35:39,110
And that's why the miners were so angry when they gave her a state funeral, right?

310
00:35:39,550 --> 00:35:45,016
Because she completely ruined their community and gave them nothing back.

311
00:35:45,918 --> 00:35:56,568
It wasn't as though she said, well, you know, I'm taking the coal industry away from you, but instead I'm going to put this in its stead so you can earn money and maintain your community.

312
00:35:56,849 --> 00:35:58,431
No, she just took everything off.

313
00:35:58,646 --> 00:36:14,907
Now I was at the process of that, I was teaching at the time at an FE college, Further Education college, and when she took away all the support for industry, the Chamber of Commerce were going berserk.

314
00:36:15,527 --> 00:36:21,195
There were so many collapses of businesses.

315
00:36:21,175 --> 00:36:27,862
And the unemployment rose from 6% to 16% in six months.

316
00:36:28,403 --> 00:36:29,664
That's what happened.

317
00:36:29,684 --> 00:36:41,460
And if you look at the process, what happened in Chile and to Russia after the collapse of communism, you'll see that's exactly what they did, and it just created enormous poverty.

318
00:36:41,880 --> 00:36:49,630
And it's something that sticks in the craw of somebody like Putin, that they were so humiliated.

319
00:36:50,150 --> 00:36:53,335
Sorry about that.

320
00:36:53,355 --> 00:36:58,262
I'm on my hockey horse, as you can see.

321
00:36:58,282 --> 00:37:10,199
And of course, when it comes to suppression, when it comes to opposition, then we're beginning to see this suppression and suppression and oppression.

322
00:37:10,900 --> 00:37:17,389
So a bill has just been passed, you see, the crime, what is it, the police crime sentencing and courts bill.

323
00:37:18,161 --> 00:37:21,909
you can now be arrested for being a single protester.

324
00:37:23,012 --> 00:37:26,478
If you go out with a placard and protest, you can be arrested.

325
00:37:27,822 --> 00:37:32,451
So you can see, they don't like people who try to buck the system.

326
00:37:33,893 --> 00:37:37,842
Okay, now the real point of this, from a Buddhist point of view...

327
00:37:38,429 --> 00:37:54,284
but I'm really getting to it, that it would seem the report from Davos, which is where all the rich and mighty meet, was they were absolutely overjoyed at hearing about mindfulness and stress reduction.

328
00:37:55,324 --> 00:38:02,532
Because now, when their workers said, look, I'm absolutely stressed out, they said, look, take this course, we've got to sit in the corner for a while.

329
00:38:03,893 --> 00:38:08,318
And it's been called the religion of neoliberalism.

330
00:38:08,516 --> 00:38:21,800
So this amazing technique that the Buddha has given us to liberate ourselves from suffering is actually being used for a system which is so contrary to the Buddha's teachings.

331
00:38:21,880 --> 00:38:22,460
It's unbelievable.

332
00:38:23,682 --> 00:38:25,445
It's based on greed, for instance.

333
00:38:27,164 --> 00:38:31,592
So finally, you know, just like what can we do in this sort of situation?

334
00:38:31,771 --> 00:38:36,981
Well, it's the usual thing about consumerism because that's what's powering it, right?

335
00:38:37,001 --> 00:38:43,293
And remember that boredom is a big underlying engine to greed.

336
00:38:43,813 --> 00:38:50,184
Because, you know, if you're in a bored state, well, you go out and do some, what is it, retail therapy again.

337
00:38:50,570 --> 00:38:55,114
And it's a case of recognizing that what we buy is a fuel in the system.

338
00:38:55,134 --> 00:39:01,559
That doesn't mean you can't buy anything, but you might just consider where it's made, you see, and whether you need it.

339
00:39:03,802 --> 00:39:20,356
And the other thing is that from a personal point of view, you know, just to get back to generosity, have you noticed, you might not have noticed, but when you do something good for yourself, like you might buy some thermal underwear,

340
00:39:21,181 --> 00:39:25,547
No, I say that because I did it for myself.

341
00:39:26,307 --> 00:39:33,077
And it feels so, it's fantastic, it feels so warm, you know, you think, my God, why haven't I discovered this before?

342
00:39:34,059 --> 00:39:39,365
And of course, and you feel very good about yourself, you've been so careful, kind to yourself, you see.

343
00:39:40,166 --> 00:39:48,858
Now, if I had bought thermal underwear for somebody else, and they had said, I'm so, you know, I'm really grateful for this thermal underwear,

344
00:39:49,666 --> 00:39:52,969
The joy that I get from that would have lasted longer.

345
00:39:53,329 --> 00:39:53,891
Check it out.

346
00:39:54,271 --> 00:39:57,894
When I do something for myself, I get a joy, right?

347
00:39:58,054 --> 00:39:59,177
And it lasts a little bit.

348
00:39:59,197 --> 00:40:03,862
But when I do something generous and beautiful for somebody else, it lasts.

349
00:40:04,121 --> 00:40:12,291
And every time I bring that to mind, it gives me that little lift of the joy of having brought some happiness into somebody else's life.

350
00:40:13,391 --> 00:40:17,597
And I want to quote the Buddha here, and it's around eating.

351
00:40:18,978 --> 00:40:31,340
If beings knew, as I know, the results of giving and sharing, they would not eat without having given, nor would the stain of miserliness overcome their minds.

352
00:40:33,402 --> 00:40:43,922
Even if it were their last bite, their last mouthful, they would not eat without having shared if there was somebody to receive the gift.

353
00:40:45,134 --> 00:40:54,009
But because beings do not know, as I know, the results of giving and sharing, they eat without having given.

354
00:40:54,028 --> 00:41:00,800
The stain of miserliness overcomes their minds.

355
00:41:00,820 --> 00:41:04,387
Did that look good?

356
00:41:04,407 --> 00:41:05,027
Okay, so I'm done.

357
00:41:05,369 --> 00:41:07,733
I'm done with Neil deGrasse Tyson, okay?

358
00:41:09,028 --> 00:41:16,905
So the next one is something which brings us into what's happening in Ukraine.

359
00:41:17,525 --> 00:41:23,577
So what was the Buddha's position when it came to war?

360
00:41:25,447 --> 00:41:30,293
So he himself was involved in three conflicts of one sort or another.

361
00:41:31,054 --> 00:41:38,083
The first one was up in his own clan, the Sakya's and the Kaliya's.

362
00:41:38,583 --> 00:41:47,355
So they shared this river and they got into a real argy-bargy about it and they were going to go and have a fisticuffs, you know.

363
00:41:47,335 --> 00:41:58,807
And he was up there, he seemed to be up there, and he must have talked to him about the unwholesomeness, the unskillfulness of war, etc.

364
00:42:00,409 --> 00:42:07,898
And what he asked them was, what is more precious, the water in the river or the blood in your veins?

365
00:42:07,918 --> 00:42:15,586
And this seemed to have brought them to their senses around the old conference table, and they came to an agreement over things.

366
00:42:17,237 --> 00:42:24,068
There's another case where King Piduddhava, who was the king of Kosala.

367
00:42:24,588 --> 00:42:28,454
Now his father, Pasenadi, was a great supporter of the Buddha.

368
00:42:28,474 --> 00:42:31,197
And this young fellow, he was now the owner there.

369
00:42:31,998 --> 00:42:35,103
Now he had asked for a bride from the Sakyans.

370
00:42:35,123 --> 00:42:38,248
So it was aristocracy, sort of marrying into another.

371
00:42:38,588 --> 00:42:41,092
The Sakyans were vassals of Kosala.

372
00:42:41,873 --> 00:42:44,476
They were under the Kosalan king, Piduddhava.

373
00:42:44,456 --> 00:42:52,746
Well, it came about that he came to know that this woman he'd married was actually a low caste.

374
00:42:53,547 --> 00:42:54,469
And so he was very angry.

375
00:42:55,110 --> 00:42:59,655
So he vowed to wipe out the succulents.

376
00:42:59,675 --> 00:43:01,358
And he got on his four-fold army.

377
00:43:02,018 --> 00:43:06,364
His elephants, his chariots, his cavalry, and his infantry.

378
00:43:06,664 --> 00:43:10,652
The Buddha must have heard about this because he went to speak to him.

379
00:43:10,672 --> 00:43:20,954
And who knows what he said, but probably on an ethical basis, the idea of rebirth, you know, with hatred, revenge in your heart, is going to have this ongoing problem.

380
00:43:21,456 --> 00:43:22,237
So he turned back.

381
00:43:23,019 --> 00:43:25,585
He no sooner got back than he got back on his elephant.

382
00:43:25,565 --> 00:43:51,268
and the Buddha's out there again and this time he was able again to turn round he no sooner got back than he got back on his elephant and the Buddha's out there again and he convinces him to turn back he gets on his elephant again and the Buddha said I can't do any more so he went and he razed the village, the town of the capital of Atta which was the capital of the Sakins

383
00:43:51,248 --> 00:43:53,831
I don't know whether he killed anybody.

384
00:43:53,911 --> 00:43:55,773
I mean, presumably they just ran off.

385
00:43:56,333 --> 00:44:00,358
And him, while he damaged the city and then went back home.

386
00:44:02,039 --> 00:44:04,742
And they built another capital, it seems.

387
00:44:05,384 --> 00:44:09,469
Interestingly enough, one is in India and one is in Nepal.

388
00:44:09,489 --> 00:44:12,172
So there's only a brick wall there.

389
00:44:12,893 --> 00:44:17,458
But I mean, at least it sort of gives some sort of credence to that story.

390
00:44:19,581 --> 00:44:26,331
So again, he's trying to stop war, and I presume his arguments are to do with morality.

391
00:44:27,172 --> 00:44:40,829
The final one is a rather interesting one, where Ajatasattu, who was the son of Bimbisara, who was also a great supporter of the Buddha, and the king of Magadha, which is the Bhagavad Gita.

392
00:44:41,097 --> 00:44:57,532
And he sent his counselor to talk to the Buddha and ask him, it's crazy when you think about it, he asked the Buddha, was it a good time to attack the Vajjian Confederacy?

393
00:44:58,032 --> 00:45:03,056
And the Buddha did not reply, it might be good, it might not.

394
00:45:03,077 --> 00:45:11,103
He gave principles for the monastic order as to what makes a society strong.

395
00:45:11,083 --> 00:45:15,248
I haven't written them down here because we don't need to go into that detail.

396
00:45:15,929 --> 00:45:29,567
So this particular counselor went back to Ajatasattu and he said, well, he gave these principles for a strong sangha, a monastic sangha, so he must be telling us that the badges are strong.

397
00:45:29,907 --> 00:45:31,809
So that's how they interpreted it.

398
00:45:32,126 --> 00:45:46,137
But what they did was they sent in the CIA and by bribery and setting people up against another, they finally undermined the Confederacy and he walked in and took it.

399
00:45:47,246 --> 00:45:55,958
So, in all these cases, the Buddha is definitely working against conflict, against any form of conflict.

400
00:45:55,978 --> 00:46:05,253
Now, some writers will argue, well, I mean, no way would he have supported an offensive war, but he would have supported a defensive war.

401
00:46:05,753 --> 00:46:09,338
But frankly, I don't really get that.

402
00:46:09,358 --> 00:46:15,347
Now, these two kings I've mentioned, Patsanadi of

403
00:46:15,782 --> 00:46:22,030
of Kosala which was up towards Delhi and Bimbisara down here in the Ganges.

404
00:46:23,853 --> 00:46:27,516
Bimbisara, this Bimbisara attacked Kosala, right?

405
00:46:28,318 --> 00:46:29,860
And he defeated them.

406
00:46:29,880 --> 00:46:34,686
But Pashtunadi got his army together and came back and smacked old Bimbisara.

407
00:46:35,206 --> 00:46:38,369
In those days, believe it or not, armies just fought against each other.

408
00:46:38,851 --> 00:46:42,195
There's a Greek ambassador

409
00:46:42,175 --> 00:47:01,585
who says that he watched a battle between two armies and while that was happening the farmers were still working around them Those were the days of chivalry So now, if the Buddha

410
00:47:01,784 --> 00:47:07,012
See, now, by this time, especially as his order grew, his order is everywhere, right?

411
00:47:07,032 --> 00:47:16,266
There are Buddhist monks everywhere, there are disciples, there are lay disciples, just stretching right across the north of that Gangetic plain.

412
00:47:16,827 --> 00:47:21,614
It doesn't go, I don't think it goes as far as Calcutta, but definitely from about...

413
00:47:21,594 --> 00:47:32,554
a bit to the east of present-day Benares, all the way up to Delhi, because he gives the talk to people called Kurus who live close to present-day Delhi.

414
00:47:32,775 --> 00:47:35,380
So he's walking around this whole area all his life.

415
00:47:36,300 --> 00:47:38,304
He's always on the move.

416
00:47:40,259 --> 00:47:50,195
So, if he were to say, if he were to side with anybody, so this is the Buddha being pragmatic, right?

417
00:47:50,315 --> 00:48:01,034
Obviously, the king who he was arguing against would have kicked all his monks and all his members out of his kingdom, right?

418
00:48:01,235 --> 00:48:07,172
Now, that's to make the Buddha sound as though he's a sort of schemer, right?

419
00:48:07,192 --> 00:48:10,501
But on the other hand, he is pragmatic, right?

420
00:48:10,521 --> 00:48:16,458
He's right there grounded in what would happen if he were to support one king against another.

421
00:48:16,742 --> 00:48:27,036
But there's, I think, a deeper reason why he doesn't talk about defensive or offensive war.

422
00:48:27,056 --> 00:48:31,862
And that's because his teaching is always concerned with the individual.

423
00:48:32,123 --> 00:48:33,204
It's always about you.

424
00:48:34,025 --> 00:48:45,179
And I think what he would say to somebody who was going to a war would be, can you kill another human being without anger or hatred in your heart?

425
00:48:45,547 --> 00:48:53,416
And if you can't do that, then there's going to be consequences for you and the violence will carry on.

426
00:48:54,858 --> 00:49:00,724
The Chinese have a saying, those who seek revenge should prepare two graves.

427
00:49:02,286 --> 00:49:07,711
So there's no end to that violence if you're going to hit violence with violence.

428
00:49:11,036 --> 00:49:12,416
Now,

429
00:49:14,219 --> 00:49:24,233
In Buddhist history, in China for instance, the monks, the orders and the Buddhists were persecuted or supported depending on the winds of the emperor.

430
00:49:25,114 --> 00:49:32,025
And that's why the monks disappeared into the jungles and whatnot and developed this form of fighting Kung Fu.

431
00:49:32,106 --> 00:49:41,077
And the idea was that, of course, you stop the enemy from damaging you, from killing you, etc., but without any hatred, without anything in your heart.

432
00:49:41,878 --> 00:49:45,543
And this ethos passed over to Japan.

433
00:49:46,163 --> 00:49:53,592
And there's the story of a samurai who has beaten his opponent, and he's raised his sword to cleave him in two, and he walks away.

434
00:49:53,652 --> 00:49:58,097
And when they ask him why did he do that, he said, I felt angry.

435
00:49:58,077 --> 00:49:59,478
Okay?

436
00:49:59,498 --> 00:50:05,144
So here's, I think this is a more nuanced way of looking at the Buddha.

437
00:50:05,545 --> 00:50:09,809
He's not supporting any sort of war, right?

438
00:50:10,289 --> 00:50:19,541
But if you are going to go to war, then you have to be very careful that you're doing it not from the heart of hatred, revenge, etc.

439
00:50:24,286 --> 00:50:28,050
I read an article actually about that.

440
00:50:29,887 --> 00:50:35,112
It's very difficult to kill a living human being.

441
00:50:35,992 --> 00:50:39,096
To actually stand in front of them and kill that person.

442
00:50:39,556 --> 00:50:41,918
And they did a survey of American soldiers.

443
00:50:43,340 --> 00:50:47,304
And I can't remember the percentage, but it was shockingly high.

444
00:50:47,784 --> 00:50:52,710
It was around about, you know, 45-50% did not shoot to kill.

445
00:50:53,050 --> 00:50:56,114
They either shot over the enemy or around the enemy.

446
00:50:56,134 --> 00:50:56,894
They actually shoot to kill.

447
00:50:57,034 --> 00:50:59,117
They couldn't bring themselves around to doing that.

448
00:50:59,418 --> 00:51:28,344
so that tells you that it's something very difficult for a human being to do and the way that they can do it is by giving them an object of hate so if you want to get a Russian soldier in a real real hateful mood what you say is your enemy are Nazis because if you remember they lost 20 million in the war against the German invasion and that's what happened

449
00:51:29,235 --> 00:51:35,143
So, I think that brings me to the end of my little effort here.

450
00:51:41,333 --> 00:51:57,876
So we've been through this whole business of karma and the real message, the real message in terms of ourselves, personal self, is to purify the heart of what is unwholesome and to build up wholesomeness.

451
00:51:58,057 --> 00:52:05,655
And then to try to enact that wholesomeness in society in one way or the other.

452
00:52:06,498 --> 00:52:13,114
And then the society begins to mirror back to us the wholesomeness that we have put into it.

453
00:52:14,072 --> 00:52:16,596
So we are intimately connected.

454
00:52:17,416 --> 00:52:18,639
Intimately connected.

455
00:52:18,739 --> 00:52:22,143
In fact, we are our relationships.

456
00:52:22,164 --> 00:52:23,706
That's what we actually are.

457
00:52:23,726 --> 00:52:26,088
We're in a constant state of relationship.

458
00:52:26,628 --> 00:52:30,273
Either with the physical world, the human world, the animal world.

459
00:52:31,014 --> 00:52:36,902
As soon as you get up in the morning and you hear the birds, you're in relationship.

460
00:52:36,922 --> 00:52:37,023
Yeah?

461
00:52:37,784 --> 00:52:43,371
And our job is to get that relationship into a place which is...

462
00:52:44,514 --> 00:52:51,047
which has got rid of this wrong attitude of seeking happiness in the sensual world.

463
00:52:51,588 --> 00:52:55,074
But that doesn't mean to say that we cannot enjoy life, right?

464
00:52:55,596 --> 00:52:57,760
Or that we can't enjoy pleasures.

465
00:52:58,262 --> 00:53:03,672
It's just recognizing that this is not the end-all and be-all of our existence.

466
00:53:04,882 --> 00:53:23,398
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance that they have not caused confusion and that by your commitment to the ethical and spiritual life you will be relieved of all suffering sooner rather than later.

